{"format": "tiptap/v1", "updatedAt": "2026-06-21T18:00:23.299Z", "doc": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "KL Divergence"}, {"type": "text", "text": " (Kullback-Leibler Divergence), also called "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "relative entropy"}, {"type": "text", "text": " or "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "information gain"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", is a measure from information theory that quantifies the difference between two probability distributions—it tells us how much information is lost when we approximate a true distribution "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "P"}, {"type": "text", "text": " with another distribution "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Q"}, {"type": "text", "text": ", serving as the foundation for understanding how far apart two distributions are and forming the core of variational autoencoders, generative models, and classification loss in machine learning."}]}, {"type": "image", "attrs": {"src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,", "alt": "KL Divergence — concept overview"}}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "What it is — Clear definition and intuition"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Mathematical definition:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "KL Divergence"}, {"type": "text", "text": " of distribution "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Q"}, {"type": "text", "text": " from distribution "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "P"}, {"type": "text", "text": " is:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) = Σ P(x) × log(P(x) / Q(x))"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "For continuous distributions:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) = ∫ P(x) × log(P(x) / Q(x)) dx"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Where:\n- "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "P(x)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " = true distribution (actual data)\n- "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Q(x)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " = approximating distribution (model prediction)\n- "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "log(P/Q)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " = ratio of probabilities (how different they are)\n- "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Natural log"}, {"type": "text", "text": " is typically used (base e for nats)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Alternative form:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) = Σ P(x) × log(P(x)) - Σ P(x) × log(Q(x))\n           = -H(P) + H(P, Q)\n           = H(P, Q) - H(P)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Where:\n- "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "H(P)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " = entropy of P (uncertainty in true distribution)\n- "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "H(P, Q)"}, {"type": "text", "text": " = cross-entropy between P and Q"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "[cs.ox.ac](https://www.cs.ox.ac.uk/people/varun.kanade/teaching/ML-MT2017/lectures/lecture_inf_theory.pdf)"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Intuitive meaning:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "KL Divergence = extra bits needed to encode data using wrong distribution\n\nImagine compressing weather data:\n- True distribution P: Actual weather probabilities (70% sunny, 30% rainy)\n- Approximating Q: Your model's predicted probabilities (50% sunny, 50% rainy)\n\nD_KL(P||Q) = extra bits needed per message when using Q instead of P [web:317][web:321]\n\nKL divergence measures the extra number of bits needed to encode data from P if we use a code optimized for Q instead of the true distribution P [web:317]"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key insight"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": \"KL divergence is the amount of information (in bits) lost when Q is used to approximate P\"."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key properties"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "1. "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Non-negative"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) ≥ 0 for all P, Q [web:308][web:317]\n\nKL divergence is always non-negative [web:317]"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Why?"}, {"type": "text", "text": " Because it quantifies information loss—you can never have \"negative information loss\"."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "2. "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Zero if equal"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) = 0 if and only if P = Q [web:308][web:320]\n\nKL divergence is equal to 0 when the predicted probability distribution is the same as the actual probability distribution [web:320]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "3. "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Asymmetric"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "yaml"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) ≠ D_KL(Q||P) [web:313][web:317][web:319]\n\nKL divergence is asymmetric [web:317]\n\nExample:\nTrue P: [0.9, 0.1] (mostly class 0)\nApprox Q: [0.5, 0.5] (uniform)\n\nD_KL(P||Q): Extra bits when using uniform code for highly skewed data → large\nD_KL(Q||P): Extra bits when using skewed code for uniform data → different value [web:319]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "4. "}, {"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Not a metric"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "KL divergence does NOT satisfy triangle inequality\n→ Not a true distance measure (like Euclidean distance) [web:317]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Relationship with Entropy and Cross-Entropy"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "The fundamental relationship:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Cross-Entropy = Entropy + KL Divergence\n\nH(P, Q) = H(P) + D_KL(P||Q) [web:308][web:313][web:320]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Breakdown:"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Derivation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ":"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "yaml"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) = Σ P(x) × log(P(x)/Q(x))\n           = Σ P(x) × [log(P(x)) - log(Q(x))]\n           = Σ P(x) × log(P(x)) - Σ P(x) × log(Q(x))\n           = -H(P) + H(P, Q)\n           = H(P, Q) - H(P)\n\nTherefore:\nD_KL(P||Q) = H(P, Q) - H(P) [web:308][web:313]"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Interpretation"}, {"type": "text", "text": ":"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "This amount by which the cross-entropy exceeds the entropy is called the relative entropy, or more commonly the Kullback-Leibler Divergence or KL Divergence [web:313]\n\nSo in short: cross-entropy is equal to the entropy plus the KL divergence [web:313]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why this matters:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Since H(P) is constant (data is fixed):\n→ Minimizing Cross-Entropy = Minimizing KL Divergence [web:313][web:320]\n\nIn that sense, KL divergence is the difference between cross-entropy and entropy [web:322]"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Key insight"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": \"KL divergence measures the difference between cross-entropy and entropy\"."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How to compute — Step-by-step examples"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Example 1: Discrete distributions"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "yaml"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "True P: [0.5, 0.3, 0.2]\nApprox Q: [0.4, 0.4, 0.2]\n\nD_KL(P||Q) = Σ P(x) × log(P(x)/Q(x))\n           = 0.5 × log(0.5/0.4) + 0.3 × log(0.3/0.4) + 0.2 × log(0.2/0.2)\n           = 0.5 × log(1.25) + 0.3 × log(0.75) + 0.2 × log(1.0)\n           = 0.5 × 0.223 + 0.3 × (-0.288) + 0.2 × 0\n           = 0.112 - 0.086 + 0\n           = 0.026 nats\n\nInterpretation: Small KL → Q is close to P"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Example 2: Binary case"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "yaml"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "True P: [0.9, 0.1]\nApprox Q: [0.5, 0.5]\n\nD_KL(P||Q) = 0.9 × log(0.9/0.5) + 0.1 × log(0.1/0.5)\n           = 0.9 × log(1.8) + 0.1 × log(0.2)\n           = 0.9 × 0.588 + 0.1 × (-1.609)\n           = 0.529 - 0.161\n           = 0.368 nats\n\nInterpretation: Medium KL → Q moderately different from P"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Example 3: Asymmetry demonstration"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "yaml"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "True P: [0.9, 0.1]\nApprox Q: [0.5, 0.5]\n\nD_KL(P||Q) = 0.368 (calculated above)\n\nD_KL(Q||P) = 0.5 × log(0.5/0.9) + 0.5 × log(0.5/0.1)\n           = 0.5 × log(0.556) + 0.5 × log(5.0)\n           = 0.5 × (-0.588) + 0.5 × 1.609\n           = -0.294 + 0.805\n           = 0.511 nats\n\nNote: D_KL(P||Q) = 0.368 ≠ D_KL(Q||P) = 0.511 [web:317][web:319]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Python implementation"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Computing KL divergence:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import numpy as np\n\n# True distribution P\nP = np.array([0.5, 0.3, 0.2])\n\n# Approximate distribution Q\nQ = np.array([0.4, 0.4, 0.2])\n\n# KL Divergence (nats)\nkl_div = np.sum(P * np.log(P / Q))\nprint(f\"KL Divergence: {kl_div:.3f} nats\")  # ≈ 0.026 nats"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Relationship verification:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "python"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "import numpy as np\n\nP = np.array([0.5, 0.3, 0.2])\nQ = np.array([0.4, 0.4, 0.2])\n\n# Entropy H(P)\nH_P = -np.sum(P * np.log(P))\n\n# Cross-Entropy H(P, Q)\nH_PQ = -np.sum(P * np.log(Q))\n\n# KL Divergence\nKL = np.sum(P * np.log(P / Q))\n\n# Verify: H(P, Q) = H(P) + KL\nprint(f\"Entropy H(P): {H_P:.3f}\")\nprint(f\"Cross-Entropy H(P,Q): {H_PQ:.3f}\")\nprint(f\"KL Divergence: {KL:.3f}\")\nprint(f\"Check: H(P) + KL = {H_P + KL:.3f} == H(P,Q) = {H_PQ:.3f}\")  # Should match!"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why it matters — Importance in Generative AI"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "KL Divergence is critical for:"}]}, {"type": "table", "content": [{"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "ML Application"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "How KL applies"}]}]}, {"type": "tableHeader", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": " "}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "VAEs"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Minimize KL between learned latent distribution Q(z"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "x) and prior P(z) = Normal(0,1)"}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Classification"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Cross-entropy loss minimizes KL between true and predicted distributions"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": " "}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "GANs"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Generative models trained by minimizing KL divergence between real and generated distributions"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": " "}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Information Theory"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Measures information loss when approximating distributions"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": " "}]}]}]}, {"type": "tableRow", "content": [{"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Data Compression"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Extra bits needed when using wrong encoding scheme"}]}]}, {"type": "tableCell", "attrs": {"colspan": 1, "rowspan": 1, "colwidth": null, "align": null}, "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": " "}]}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Real example"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Training VAEs uses KL divergence to regularize the latent space, ensuring encoder outputs match a standard Gaussian prior for smooth generation."}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Asymmetry explained"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 3}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Why KL is asymmetric:"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "D_KL(P||Q) ≠ D_KL(Q||P)\n\nDirection matters! [web:317][web:319]\n\nP||Q: Extra bits when using Q to approximate P (true → model)\nQ||P: Extra bits when using P to approximate Q (model → true)"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Intuitive example"}, {"type": "text", "text": ":"}]}, {"type": "codeBlock", "attrs": {"language": "text"}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "True P: Highly skewed [0.9, 0.1]\nApprox Q: Uniform [0.5, 0.5]\n\nD_KL(P||Q):\n- Using uniform code for skewed data → large penalty for rare events\n- 0.9 × log(0.9/0.5) = 0.529 (big penalty)\n- 0.1 × log(0.1/0.5) = -0.161 (small gain)\n- Total: 0.368\n\nD_KL(Q||P):\n- Using skewed code for uniform data → moderate penalty\n- 0.5 × log(0.5/0.9) = -0.294 (small gain)\n- 0.5 × log(0.5/0.1) = 0.805 (big penalty)\n- Total: 0.511\n\nDifferent because penalties depend on which distribution is \"true\" [web:317][web:319]"}]}, {"type": "heading", "attrs": {"level": 2}, "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Key takeaways"}]}, {"type": "orderedList", "attrs": {"start": 1, "type": null}, "content": [{"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "KL Divergence formula"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": D_KL(P||Q) = Σ P(x) log(P(x)/Q(x))"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Meaning"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Extra bits needed when using Q instead of P for encoding"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Also called"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Relative entropy, information gain"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Non-negative"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": D_KL ≥ 0 (always)"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Zero if equal"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": D_KL = 0 only when P = Q"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Asymmetric"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": D_KL(P||Q) ≠ D_KL(Q||P)"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Not a metric"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Doesn't satisfy triangle inequality"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "KL = Cross-Entropy - Entropy"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": D_KL(P||Q) = H(P,Q) - H(P)"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Minimize CE = Minimize KL"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Since H(P) is constant, optimizing cross-entropy minimizes KL"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "VAEs"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Minimize KL between latent distribution and Gaussian prior"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Classification"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Cross-entropy loss minimizes KL between true and predicted"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "GANs"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Minimize KL between real and generated distributions"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Information lost"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": D_KL(P||Q) = information lost when Q approximates P"}]}]}, {"type": "listItem", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "marks": [{"type": "bold"}], "text": "Data compression"}, {"type": "text", "text": ": Extra bits needed when using wrong encoding scheme"}]}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "For Generative AI, KL Divergence is absolutely fundamental: VAEs use KL to regularize latent spaces and enforce Gaussian priors, GANs optimize to minimize KL between generated and real distributions, classification models minimize cross-entropy (equivalent to minimizing KL), and information-theoretic measures of uncertainty rely on KL—making it essential for understanding how generative models learn probability distributions and generate realistic data; understanding KL Divergence is critical for mastering how neural networks model uncertainty and learn distributions."}]}]}}